\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b1\i0 Role}
\par\plain \f2\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f2\fs24\b0\i0 The Role is the part played by this character in your story.  It's often the character's occupation, since many characters' story context hinges on their job or work.  The role may be stereotypical\hich\f2 \emdash \loch\f2  'private eye' brings to mind a composite image of thousands of fictional characters.  The character himself, though, should be as unique as you can make him.}
\par\plain \f2\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f2\fs24\b0\i0 The roles of major characters are often dictated by the genre.  For example, a western suggests a cowboy.  But placing a character in an unusual milieu can be very effective, as in the TV series }{\f4\fs24\b0\i1 McCloud}{\f2\fs24\b0\i0 , in which cowboy deputy McCloud is loaned to the NYPD and relocated from Taos, New Mexico to urban New York.}
\par\plain \f2\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f2\fs24\b0\i0 Another useful trick to liven up a role is to cross gender norms in casting the part, such as with a lady alligator wrestler, or a man who runs a wedding dress shop.}
\par\plain \f2\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b1\i0 Story Role}
\par\plain \f2\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f2\fs24\b0\i0 The story role is the relative importance of the character's part  to the story's development.}
\par\plain \f2\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f2\fs24\b0\i0 The more significant a character is to the story, the more fully developed he or she should be.  The characters in major roles should ideally be so rounded out that they 'come alive'.  Writing scenes for such a well-developed character often becomes a matter of putting him in a situation and watching how he reacts.}
