\pard\plain \intbl\itap1\tx-720\ri0\sl240\slmult0\ql{\f2\fs22\b0\i0 Shadow}\cell 
\pard\plain \intbl\itap1\tx-720\ri0\sl240\slmult0\ql{\f2\fs24\b0\i0 The Shadow archetype is a negative figure, representing things we don't like and would like to eliminate.}
\par\plain \intbl\itap1\f2\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain \intbl\itap1{\f2\fs24\b0\i0 The shadow often takes the form of the antagonist in a story.  But not all antagonists are villains; sometimes the antagonist is a good guy whose goals disagree with the protagonist's.  If the antagonist is a villain, though, he's a shadow.}
\par\plain \intbl\itap1\f2\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain \intbl\itap1{\f2\fs24\b0\i0 The shadow is the worthy opponent with whom the hero must struggle. In a conflict between hero and villain, the fight is to the end; one or the other must be destroyed or rendered impotent.}
\par\plain \intbl\itap1\f2\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain \intbl\itap1{\f2\fs24\b0\i0 While the shadow is a negative force in the story, it's important to remember that no man is a villain in his own eyes.  In fact, the shadow frequently sees himself as a hero, and the story's hero as his villain.}\cell{
